content:
Certainly! Below is an example of how you can create a simple digital clock using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.

### HTML
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Digital Clock</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div class="clock">
        <div id="time"></div>
    </div>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### CSS (styles.css)
```css
body {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    height: 100vh;
    margin: 0;
    background-color: #282c34;
    color: white;
    font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
}

.clock {
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 60px;
    padding: 20px;
    border-radius: 10px;
    background-color: #333;
    box-shadow: 0 0 20px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
}

#time {
    font-size: 2em;
}
```

### JavaScript (script.js)
```javascript
function updateTime() {
    const now = new Date();
    const hours = String(now.getHours()).padStart(2, '0');
    const minutes = String(now.getMinutes()).padStart(2, '0');
    const seconds = String(now.getSeconds()).padStart(2, '0');
    const timeString = `${hours}:${minutes}:${seconds}`;

    document.getElementById('time').textContent = timeString;
}

setInterval(updateTime, 1000);
updateTime(); // Initial call to set the time immediately on load
```

### Explanation
- **HTML**: Sets up the basic structure of the webpage, including a `div` to display the time.
- **CSS**: Styles the clock with a centered layout, a dark background, and white text for clarity.
- **JavaScript**: 
  - The `updateTime` function fetches the current time using the `Date` object.
  - It formats the hours, minutes, and seconds to be two digits each (e.g., `08:05:09`).
  - It updates the `time` element every second using `setInterval`.

This will display a digital clock on a webpage, continuously updating every second to show the current time.
